          <h2>Lesson 1: Osmoregulation — Water &amp; Ion Balance</h2>

          <p class="section-intro">
            Osmoregulation is the control of water and dissolved solute concentrations in the
            body fluids. It is one of the most popular choices for the AS 91604 internal because
            of the clear, well-documented feedback mechanisms involving the kidneys.
          </p>

          <div class="internal-note">
            <svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <path d="M12 8v1M12 12v4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            <div>
              <strong>Overview lesson:</strong> This is a survey, not a deep dive. You are
              learning what osmoregulation involves so you can decide whether to choose it
              for your internal. The independent research is yours to do.
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── What Is Being Regulated? ── -->
          <h3>What Is Being Regulated?</h3>

          <p>
            The <strong>osmolarity</strong> (concentration of dissolved solutes) of blood and
            tissue fluids must be kept within a narrow range — approximately
            <strong>300 mOsm/L</strong> in humans. If blood becomes too dilute (hypotonic),
            cells swell and can burst. If blood becomes too concentrated (hypertonic), cells
            shrink and lose function. Either extreme is life-threatening.
          </p>
          <p>
            Water balance is intimately linked to ion balance — particularly
            <strong>sodium (Na⁺)</strong> and <strong>potassium (K⁺)</strong>. The kidneys
            regulate both simultaneously.
          </p>


          <!-- ── The Feedback Loop ── -->
          <h3>The Negative Feedback Loop</h3>

          <div class="feedback-loop-summary">
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Stimulus</span>
              <span class="loop-detail">Blood osmolarity rises (e.g. after eating salty food, sweating, or not drinking enough water)</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Receptor / Sensor</span>
              <span class="loop-detail"><strong>Osmoreceptors</strong> in the <strong>hypothalamus</strong> detect the increase in blood solute concentration (they physically shrink as water leaves the cells by osmosis)</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Control Centre</span>
              <span class="loop-detail"><strong>Hypothalamus</strong> signals the <strong>posterior pituitary gland</strong> to release <strong>antidiuretic hormone (ADH)</strong> — also called vasopressin</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Effectors</span>
              <span class="loop-detail">
                <strong>Kidneys</strong> — specifically the <strong>collecting ducts</strong> and <strong>distal convoluted tubules</strong> of the nephron. ADH causes insertion of <strong>aquaporin-2</strong> water channels into the collecting duct membranes, increasing water reabsorption back into the blood
              </span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Response</span>
              <span class="loop-detail">More water reabsorbed → blood osmolarity decreases back toward set point → small volume of concentrated urine produced. When osmolarity falls, ADH secretion decreases and more dilute urine is produced</span>
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Additional Detail ── -->
          <h3>Key Details for Depth</h3>

          <p>
            If you choose osmoregulation, these are the concepts you will need to research
            independently for Merit and Excellence:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>The nephron:</strong> The functional unit of the kidney — understand glomerular filtration, selective reabsorption in the proximal convoluted tubule, the loop of Henle (countercurrent multiplier creating the medullary concentration gradient), and ADH-controlled reabsorption in the collecting duct</li>
            <li><strong>Aquaporins:</strong> ADH triggers insertion of aquaporin-2 channels into collecting duct cell membranes via exocytosis of vesicles — this is the molecular mechanism</li>
            <li><strong>Aldosterone:</strong> A second hormone from the adrenal cortex that increases Na⁺ reabsorption in the distal tubule, pulling water with it (the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system, or RAAS)</li>
            <li><strong>Thirst response:</strong> The hypothalamus also triggers the sensation of thirst when osmolarity rises — driving behavioural water intake</li>
          </ul>


          <!-- ── When It Goes Wrong ── -->
          <h3>When Osmoregulation Fails</h3>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Diabetes insipidus:</strong> Insufficient ADH production (central) or kidneys not responding to ADH (nephrogenic) — produces large volumes of very dilute urine and extreme thirst. Not related to blood glucose or diabetes mellitus</li>
            <li><strong>Hyponatraemia:</strong> Blood sodium too low — often from drinking excessive water without electrolytes (e.g. during endurance sports). Cells swell, brain swells, can be fatal</li>
            <li><strong>Dehydration:</strong> Insufficient water intake or excessive loss — blood osmolarity rises dangerously, organs fail as cells can no longer function</li>
          </ul>


          <!-- ── Assessment Box ── -->
          <div class="topic-assessment">
            <div class="topic-pros">
              <h4>Strengths</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Very well-resourced — covered extensively in Campbell Biology and all NZ textbooks</li>
                <li>Clear, nameable components at every level (osmoreceptors, hypothalamus, posterior pituitary, ADH, aquaporin-2, nephron)</li>
                <li>The ADH mechanism gives you molecular detail for Excellence (vesicle fusion, aquaporin insertion)</li>
                <li>Strong examples of breakdown (diabetes insipidus, hyponatraemia)</li>
                <li>Probably the most popular internal choice nationally</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="topic-considerations">
              <h4>Things to Watch</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>You need to understand the nephron — this is more anatomy to learn than thermoregulation</li>
                <li>Don't confuse diabetes insipidus with diabetes mellitus — they are completely different conditions</li>
                <li>The RAAS (aldosterone) pathway adds depth but also complexity — decide whether to include it based on your confidence level</li>
                <li>Make sure you explain <em>how</em> aquaporins work, not just that they exist</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>


