          <h2>Lesson 2: Blood Calcium Regulation</h2>

          <p class="section-intro">
            Blood calcium (Ca²⁺) is maintained at approximately <strong>2.2–2.6 mmol/L</strong>.
            This is a beautifully clean example of homeostasis — two antagonistic hormones from
            the thyroid and parathyroid glands, working in opposition, just like insulin and
            glucagon. If you liked the elegance of glucose regulation, calcium may appeal to you.
          </p>

          <div class="internal-note">
            <svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <path d="M12 8v1M12 12v4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            <div>
              <strong>Parallel structure:</strong> Notice the similarities to glucose homeostasis —
              two antagonistic hormones, a set point, and negative feedback. This makes it
              easier to write about because the structure mirrors what you already know.
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── What Is Being Regulated? ── -->
          <h3>What Is Being Regulated?</h3>

          <p>
            The concentration of <strong>ionised calcium (Ca²⁺)</strong> in the blood. Calcium
            is not just about bones — it is essential for:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Muscle contraction:</strong> Ca²⁺ triggers the sliding filament mechanism in both skeletal and cardiac muscle</li>
            <li><strong>Nerve impulse transmission:</strong> Required for neurotransmitter release at synapses</li>
            <li><strong>Blood clotting:</strong> Ca²⁺ is a cofactor in the clotting cascade</li>
            <li><strong>Cell signalling:</strong> Acts as a second messenger in many intracellular pathways</li>
            <li><strong>Bone structure:</strong> 99% of body calcium is stored in bones as calcium phosphate (hydroxyapatite)</li>
          </ul>


          <!-- ── The Feedback Loop ── -->
          <h3>The Negative Feedback Loop</h3>

          <div class="feedback-loop-summary">
            <div class="loop-component loop-component--split">
              <span class="loop-label">Stimulus — Too Low</span>
              <span class="loop-detail">Blood Ca²⁺ falls below ~2.2 mmol/L</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Receptor &amp; Control Centre</span>
              <span class="loop-detail"><strong>Parathyroid glands</strong> (four small glands on the posterior surface of the thyroid) detect low blood Ca²⁺ via <strong>calcium-sensing receptors (CaSR)</strong> on their cell surfaces</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Hormone Released</span>
              <span class="loop-detail"><strong>Parathyroid hormone (PTH)</strong> is secreted into the blood</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Effectors (three targets)</span>
              <span class="loop-detail">
                <strong>1. Bones:</strong> PTH stimulates <strong>osteoclasts</strong> to break down bone matrix, releasing Ca²⁺ into the blood<br/>
                <strong>2. Kidneys:</strong> PTH increases Ca²⁺ reabsorption in the distal tubule (less calcium lost in urine) and activates vitamin D<br/>
                <strong>3. Intestine:</strong> Active vitamin D (calcitriol, activated by PTH in the kidneys) increases Ca²⁺ absorption from food in the small intestine
              </span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Response</span>
              <span class="loop-detail">Blood Ca²⁺ rises back toward set point → parathyroid glands detect the increase → PTH secretion decreases (negative feedback)</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h4>The Antagonistic Hormone: Calcitonin</h4>

          <p>
            When blood Ca²⁺ is <strong>too high</strong>, the <strong>thyroid gland</strong>
            (specifically the <strong>parafollicular C cells</strong>) releases
            <strong>calcitonin</strong>. Calcitonin opposes PTH:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Inhibits osteoclast activity → less calcium released from bone</li>
            <li>Reduces Ca²⁺ reabsorption in the kidneys → more calcium lost in urine</li>
            <li>The net effect: blood Ca²⁺ decreases back toward the set point</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            This is the same antagonistic pattern as insulin/glucagon — two hormones pulling
            in opposite directions to maintain balance.
          </p>


          <!-- ── When It Goes Wrong ── -->
          <h3>When Calcium Regulation Fails</h3>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Hypocalcaemia</strong> (Ca²⁺ too low) — muscle cramps, tingling, cardiac arrhythmias, tetany (uncontrolled muscle contractions). Often caused by vitamin D deficiency or parathyroid removal during thyroid surgery</li>
            <li><strong>Hypercalcaemia</strong> (Ca²⁺ too high) — kidney stones, bone pain, fatigue, confusion, cardiac arrest in extreme cases. Often caused by overactive parathyroid glands (hyperparathyroidism) or certain cancers</li>
            <li><strong>Osteoporosis:</strong> Chronic calcium imbalance where bone resorption exceeds bone formation — bones become porous and fragile. Related to long-term PTH/calcitonin balance and declining oestrogen after menopause</li>
          </ul>


          <!-- ── Assessment Box ── -->
          <div class="topic-assessment">
            <div class="topic-pros">
              <h4>Strengths</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Clean antagonistic hormone pair (PTH vs calcitonin) — mirrors glucose regulation structure</li>
                <li>Three distinct effector targets (bone, kidney, intestine) give you plenty to write about</li>
                <li>The vitamin D activation pathway adds molecular depth for Excellence</li>
                <li>Excellent real-world relevance (osteoporosis, vitamin D deficiency)</li>
                <li>Less commonly chosen — stands out if well-written</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="topic-considerations">
              <h4>Things to Watch</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Fewer NZ-specific teaching resources than osmoregulation or thermoregulation</li>
                <li>The vitamin D activation pathway (skin → liver → kidney) adds complexity</li>
                <li>Make sure you clearly distinguish the parathyroid glands (PTH) from the thyroid gland (calcitonin) — they are separate structures</li>
                <li>Name the specific cell types: osteoclasts (break down bone), osteoblasts (build bone), parafollicular C cells (release calcitonin)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>


        <!-- ——————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————
             Lesson 3: Blood pH Regulation
             —————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— -->
        <section id="lesson-3" class="content-section fade-in-up">
