          <h2>Lesson 3: Blood pH Regulation</h2>

          <p class="section-intro">
            Blood pH is maintained at <strong>7.35–7.45</strong> — slightly alkaline. Even small
            deviations are dangerous. This is arguably the most complex homeostatic system to
            write about because it involves three simultaneous mechanisms (chemical buffers,
            respiratory compensation, and renal compensation). It is a strong choice for
            confident students aiming at Excellence.
          </p>


          <!-- ── What Is Being Regulated? ── -->
          <h3>What Is Being Regulated?</h3>

          <p>
            The <strong>hydrogen ion concentration [H⁺]</strong> of the blood, expressed as pH.
            Normal arterial blood pH is <strong>7.4</strong> (range 7.35–7.45). Below 7.35 is
            <strong>acidosis</strong>; above 7.45 is <strong>alkalosis</strong>. Death typically
            occurs below pH 6.8 or above pH 7.8.
          </p>
          <p>
            Why is this so tightly controlled? Proteins — including enzymes, haemoglobin, and
            membrane transporters — change shape when pH changes. Even 0.1 pH unit makes a
            significant difference to enzyme activity. Haemoglobin's oxygen-carrying capacity
            is directly affected by pH (the <strong>Bohr effect</strong>).
          </p>


          <!-- ── The Three Lines of Defence ── -->
          <h3>Three Lines of Defence</h3>

          <p>
            Blood pH regulation is unique among homeostatic systems because it uses three
            different mechanisms simultaneously, operating at different speeds:
          </p>

          <div class="defence-cards">
            <div class="defence-card">
              <div class="defence-card__header">
                <span class="defence-number">1</span>
                <div>
                  <h4>Chemical Buffer Systems</h4>
                  <span class="defence-speed">Instant (seconds)</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>
                The <strong>bicarbonate buffer system</strong> is the most important. Carbon
                dioxide (CO₂) produced by cellular respiration reacts with water to form
                carbonic acid (H₂CO₃), which dissociates into bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻) and H⁺:
              </p>
              <div class="equation">
                CO₂ + H₂O ⇌ H₂CO₃ ⇌ HCO₃⁻ + H⁺
              </div>
              <p>
                This equilibrium shifts to absorb or release H⁺ as needed. If blood becomes
                too acidic (too much H⁺), the reaction shifts left — H⁺ combines with HCO₃⁻
                to form CO₂, which is exhaled. If blood becomes too alkaline, the reaction
                shifts right, releasing more H⁺.
              </p>
              <p>
                Other buffers include <strong>phosphate buffers</strong> (important inside cells)
                and <strong>protein buffers</strong> (haemoglobin is a major one).
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="defence-card">
              <div class="defence-card__header">
                <span class="defence-number">2</span>
                <div>
                  <h4>Respiratory Compensation</h4>
                  <span class="defence-speed">Fast (minutes)</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>
                <strong>Peripheral chemoreceptors</strong> in the <strong>carotid bodies</strong>
                and <strong>aortic bodies</strong> detect changes in blood CO₂ and pH.
                <strong>Central chemoreceptors</strong> in the <strong>medulla oblongata</strong>
                of the brainstem detect CO₂ in the cerebrospinal fluid.
              </p>
              <p>
                When blood pH drops (too acidic, meaning too much CO₂):
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>The <strong>medulla oblongata</strong> (respiratory centre) increases breathing rate and depth</li>
                <li>More CO₂ is exhaled → the equilibrium shifts left → H⁺ decreases → pH rises</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                When blood pH rises (too alkaline, too little CO₂):
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Breathing rate decreases → CO₂ is retained → equilibrium shifts right → more H⁺ released → pH falls</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="defence-card">
              <div class="defence-card__header">
                <span class="defence-number">3</span>
                <div>
                  <h4>Renal Compensation</h4>
                  <span class="defence-speed">Slow (hours to days)</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>
                The <strong>kidneys</strong> provide the most powerful but slowest correction.
                The <strong>proximal convoluted tubule</strong> and <strong>collecting duct</strong>
                cells can:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Excrete H⁺</strong> into the urine (using H⁺-ATPase pumps) when blood is too acidic</li>
                <li><strong>Reabsorb HCO₃⁻</strong> back into the blood to replenish the buffer supply</li>
                <li><strong>Produce new HCO₃⁻</strong> from glutamine metabolism in the proximal tubule cells</li>
                <li>Conversely, excrete HCO₃⁻ and retain H⁺ when blood is too alkaline</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The kidneys are the only mechanism that can actually <em>eliminate</em> excess
                acid from the body (rather than just buffering or shifting it). This is why
                kidney failure causes severe acidosis.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── The Feedback Loop (Respiratory) ── -->
          <h3>The Respiratory Feedback Loop</h3>

          <div class="feedback-loop-summary">
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Stimulus</span>
              <span class="loop-detail">Blood pH drops below 7.35 (acidosis) — often due to increased CO₂ from exercise or metabolic processes</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Receptors</span>
              <span class="loop-detail"><strong>Peripheral chemoreceptors</strong> (carotid bodies, aortic bodies) and <strong>central chemoreceptors</strong> (medulla oblongata) detect elevated CO₂ / lowered pH</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Control Centre</span>
              <span class="loop-detail"><strong>Medulla oblongata</strong> (respiratory centre in the brainstem) — sends increased nerve impulses to the diaphragm and intercostal muscles</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Effectors</span>
              <span class="loop-detail"><strong>Diaphragm</strong> and <strong>intercostal muscles</strong> — increase breathing rate and tidal volume → more CO₂ exhaled per minute</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Response</span>
              <span class="loop-detail">Blood CO₂ decreases → equilibrium shifts left → H⁺ consumed → pH rises back toward 7.4 → chemoreceptors detect normalisation → breathing rate returns to normal (negative feedback)</span>
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── When It Goes Wrong ── -->
          <h3>When pH Regulation Fails</h3>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Respiratory acidosis:</strong> CO₂ builds up because the lungs cannot expel it fast enough (e.g. COPD, pneumonia, asthma attack). Blood pH drops. Kidneys compensate slowly by excreting more H⁺</li>
            <li><strong>Metabolic acidosis:</strong> Excess acid from metabolism (e.g. lactic acid during intense exercise, ketoacids in uncontrolled Type 1 diabetes — diabetic ketoacidosis). The respiratory system compensates by hyperventilation (Kussmaul breathing)</li>
            <li><strong>Respiratory alkalosis:</strong> Too much CO₂ exhaled — typically from hyperventilation (anxiety, altitude). Blood pH rises. Classic treatment: breathe into a paper bag to retain CO₂</li>
            <li><strong>Metabolic alkalosis:</strong> Loss of H⁺ (e.g. excessive vomiting) or excess bicarbonate intake. Respiratory compensation: breathing rate decreases</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="connection-box">
            <h4>Cross-Topic Link: Diabetes &amp; pH</h4>
            <p>
              Notice how Type 1 diabetes connects glucose homeostasis failure to pH failure.
              Without insulin, cells cannot take up glucose → switch to fat metabolism →
              ketone bodies produced → blood becomes acidic (diabetic ketoacidosis, DKA).
              This is where two homeostatic systems interact — excellent material for an
              Excellence-level discussion if you choose either glucose or pH regulation.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Assessment Box ── -->
          <div class="topic-assessment">
            <div class="topic-pros">
              <h4>Strengths</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Three interconnected mechanisms give you a lot to write about</li>
                <li>Clear, nameable receptors (carotid bodies, medulla oblongata, central and peripheral chemoreceptors)</li>
                <li>The bicarbonate buffer equation is elegant and easy to explain</li>
                <li>Strong links to other topics (exercise physiology, diabetes, respiratory disease)</li>
                <li>Rarely chosen — a well-written report on this topic would impress</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="topic-considerations">
              <h4>Things to Watch</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Most complex of the four options — requires confidence with chemistry (equilibrium, buffers)</li>
                <li>Fewer visual diagrams available in standard textbooks</li>
                <li>The renal mechanism is difficult to explain clearly at Level 8</li>
                <li>You need to decide whether to focus on the respiratory feedback loop (simpler) or cover all three mechanisms (more ambitious)</li>
                <li>Best suited for students confident in both biology and chemistry</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>


        <!-- ——————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————
             Lesson 4: Oxygen Homeostasis & Iron Regulation
             —————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— -->
        <section id="lesson-4" class="content-section fade-in-up">
          <nav class="lesson-inline-nav" aria-label="Lesson navigation">
            <a href="#lesson-3" class="lesson-inline-nav__link lesson-inline-nav__link--prev">
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M13 8H3M7 4L3 8l4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
