          <h2>Lesson 4: Oxygen Homeostasis &amp; Iron Regulation</h2>

          <p class="section-intro">
            Your body needs a steady supply of oxygen to every cell. When oxygen delivery drops
            — at altitude, after blood loss, or in anaemia — the body responds by making more
            red blood cells. This is <strong>erythropoiesis</strong>, and it is controlled by a
            clean negative feedback loop centred on the hormone <strong>erythropoietin (EPO)</strong>.
            Iron regulation is the linked system that makes erythropoiesis possible — you cannot
            build haemoglobin without iron.
          </p>

          <div class="internal-note">
            <svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <path d="M12 8v1M12 12v4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            <div>
              <strong>Two systems, one lesson:</strong> Oxygen homeostasis (the EPO loop) is the
              main feedback mechanism. Iron homeostasis (the hepcidin pathway) is a supporting
              system that modulates the EPO response. For your internal, you would frame this
              as oxygen homeostasis with iron as a linked mechanism — not two separate topics.
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── What Is Being Regulated? ── -->
          <h3>What Is Being Regulated?</h3>

          <p>
            The <strong>oxygen-carrying capacity</strong> of the blood — specifically, the number
            of circulating <strong>red blood cells (erythrocytes)</strong> and the amount of
            <strong>haemoglobin</strong> they contain. Normal haemoglobin concentration is
            approximately <strong>130–170 g/L</strong> in males and <strong>120–150 g/L</strong>
            in females.
          </p>
          <p>
            Each haemoglobin molecule contains four <strong>haem groups</strong>, and each haem
            group contains one <strong>iron (Fe²⁺) ion</strong> that reversibly binds one O₂
            molecule. This is why iron is essential — without it, haemoglobin cannot be
            assembled and oxygen cannot be transported.
          </p>


          <!-- ── The EPO Feedback Loop ── -->
          <h3>The Negative Feedback Loop: Erythropoiesis</h3>

          <div class="feedback-loop-summary">
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Stimulus</span>
              <span class="loop-detail">Blood oxygen levels fall — for example, after moving to high altitude, blood loss (haemorrhage or donation), or during chronic lung disease</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Receptor / Sensor</span>
              <span class="loop-detail"><strong>Peritubular interstitial cells</strong> in the <strong>kidneys</strong> detect reduced oxygen delivery (hypoxia) using <strong>hypoxia-inducible factor (HIF)</strong> — a transcription factor that accumulates when oxygen is low</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Control Centre &amp; Hormone</span>
              <span class="loop-detail">The kidneys (primarily — the liver produces ~10%) secrete <strong>erythropoietin (EPO)</strong> into the blood. EPO is a glycoprotein hormone</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Effector</span>
              <span class="loop-detail"><strong>Red bone marrow</strong> — EPO stimulates the proliferation and differentiation of <strong>erythrocyte precursor cells</strong> (proerythroblasts → reticulocytes → mature red blood cells). The rate of red blood cell production increases</span>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
                <path d="M10 4v12M6 12l4 4 4-4" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="loop-component">
              <span class="loop-label">Response</span>
              <span class="loop-detail">More red blood cells in circulation → increased oxygen-carrying capacity → oxygen delivery to tissues returns toward normal → kidneys detect adequate O₂ → EPO secretion decreases (negative feedback)</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="internal-note">
            <svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <path d="M12 8v1M12 12v4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            <div>
              <strong>Time lag:</strong> Unlike respiratory pH compensation (minutes) or thermoregulation
              (seconds), erythropoiesis is slow. It takes <strong>3–5 days</strong> for new red blood cells
              to appear in circulation after EPO release, and full adaptation to altitude takes
              <strong>weeks</strong>. This time lag is important to mention in an assessment.
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Iron Homeostasis ── -->
          <h3>The Linked System: Iron Regulation</h3>

          <p>
            Erythropoiesis requires a reliable supply of iron. Each new red blood cell needs
            iron for its haemoglobin, so when EPO ramps up production, iron demand surges. The
            body regulates iron through a separate but interconnected pathway centred on the
            liver hormone <strong>hepcidin</strong>.
          </p>

          <div class="defence-cards">
            <div class="defence-card">
              <div class="defence-card__header">
                <span class="defence-number">Fe</span>
                <div>
                  <h4>The Hepcidin–Ferroportin Axis</h4>
                  <span class="defence-speed">Regulated by liver</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>
                <strong>Hepcidin</strong> is a peptide hormone produced by the <strong>liver</strong>.
                It controls how much iron enters the blood by acting on <strong>ferroportin</strong>
                — the only known iron export channel on cell surfaces.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>High iron stores / adequate oxygen:</strong> Hepcidin levels rise → hepcidin binds to ferroportin on intestinal cells and macrophages → ferroportin is degraded → less iron enters the blood (iron is trapped inside cells)</li>
                <li><strong>Low iron stores / hypoxia / increased erythropoiesis:</strong> Hepcidin levels fall → ferroportin remains active → more iron is absorbed from food in the duodenum and more is released from macrophages that recycle old red blood cells</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This is how the two systems connect: when EPO drives increased red blood cell
                production, <strong>erythroferrone</strong> (a hormone released by developing
                erythroblasts in the bone marrow) suppresses hepcidin, unlocking iron stores
                to meet the demand.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="defence-card">
              <div class="defence-card__header">
                <span class="defence-number">&#x267B;</span>
                <div>
                  <h4>Iron Recycling</h4>
                  <span class="defence-speed">The body's primary iron source</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>
                Humans have <strong>no regulated mechanism for excreting iron</strong> — this is
                unusual compared with other ions. Instead, the body is remarkably efficient at
                recycling:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Old red blood cells (lifespan ~120 days) are engulfed by <strong>macrophages</strong> in the spleen and liver</li>
                <li>The iron from haemoglobin is extracted and either stored as <strong>ferritin</strong> or released via ferroportin back into the blood</li>
                <li>Released iron binds to <strong>transferrin</strong> (a transport protein) and is carried to the bone marrow to make new haemoglobin</li>
                <li>Only about <strong>1–2 mg/day</strong> of iron is absorbed from the diet — replacing small losses from skin shedding and minor bleeding</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Key Details for Depth ── -->
          <h3>Key Details for Depth</h3>

          <p>
            If you choose oxygen homeostasis, these concepts will strengthen your response
            for Merit and Excellence:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>HIF pathway:</strong> Under normal oxygen, HIF is constantly broken down (hydroxylated then ubiquitinated). In hypoxia, HIF accumulates and activates the EPO gene — this is the molecular switch. The 2019 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine was awarded for this discovery</li>
            <li><strong>Erythroferrone:</strong> The recently discovered hormone that links erythropoiesis to iron supply by suppressing hepcidin — shows how the two systems communicate</li>
            <li><strong>2,3-BPG:</strong> At altitude, red blood cells increase production of 2,3-bisphosphoglycerate, which reduces haemoglobin's affinity for oxygen → more O₂ released to tissues. This is a short-term compensatory mechanism that acts before new red blood cells are produced</li>
            <li><strong>Transferrin saturation:</strong> The percentage of transferrin bound to iron — a clinical measure that reflects the balance between iron supply and demand</li>
          </ul>


          <!-- ── When It Goes Wrong ── -->
          <h3>When Oxygen / Iron Homeostasis Fails</h3>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Iron-deficiency anaemia:</strong> The most common nutritional deficiency worldwide. Insufficient iron → insufficient haemoglobin → reduced oxygen delivery → fatigue, pallor, breathlessness. EPO rises but cannot fully compensate because the building material is missing</li>
            <li><strong>Polycythaemia:</strong> Too many red blood cells — blood becomes viscous, increasing risk of clots. Can result from chronic hypoxia (e.g. living at high altitude, chronic lung disease) or from EPO-producing tumours</li>
            <li><strong>Haemochromatosis:</strong> A genetic condition where hepcidin is underproduced or non-functional → uncontrolled iron absorption → iron overload damages the liver, heart, and pancreas</li>
            <li><strong>Chronic kidney disease:</strong> Damaged kidneys produce less EPO → severe anaemia. Treated with synthetic EPO injections (the same molecule misused in doping)</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="connection-box">
            <h4>Real-World Link: EPO &amp; Doping in Sport</h4>
            <p>
              Synthetic EPO (epoetin alfa) was developed to treat anaemia in kidney disease
              patients. Athletes discovered that injecting EPO dramatically increased red blood
              cell count and endurance performance — most infamously in professional cycling
              (the Lance Armstrong scandal). EPO doping is now detectable through blood passport
              testing, which monitors an athlete's haematocrit and reticulocyte levels over time
              for suspicious changes. This is a powerful example of what happens when a
              homeostatic set point is artificially overridden.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Assessment Box ── -->
          <div class="topic-assessment">
            <div class="topic-pros">
              <h4>Strengths</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Clean, well-defined negative feedback loop (EPO) with nameable components at every step</li>
                <li>The linked iron/hepcidin system adds depth and shows interacting homeostatic mechanisms — impressive for Excellence</li>
                <li>Compelling real-world examples (altitude training, blood doping, anaemia, kidney disease)</li>
                <li>The HIF/Nobel Prize connection provides strong molecular detail</li>
                <li>Rarely chosen — a well-written response on this topic would stand out</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="topic-considerations">
              <h4>Things to Watch</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Fewer NZ textbook resources than thermoregulation or osmoregulation — you will need to use university-level sources</li>
                <li>The hepcidin pathway is relatively recently characterised — some older textbooks do not cover it</li>
                <li>You need to clearly frame this as oxygen homeostasis with iron as a linked mechanism — not two disconnected topics</li>
                <li>The time lag (days to weeks) means the feedback loop operates differently from the rapid responses in thermoregulation or pH regulation — explain why</li>
                <li>Best suited for students comfortable with molecular detail and reading beyond the textbook</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>


